05929nam a22008295i 9781771125529DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97817711255297 a10.51644/97817711255292doi  a(DE-B1597)667681  a(OCoLC)1419790561  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aDS135.N6bR68713 2021eb 7aBIO0370002bisacsh04a940.53089/9242231 aRottenberg, Hella, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDe sigarenfabriek van Isay Rottenberg :bThe Hidden History of a Jewish Entrepreneur in Nazi Germany /cSandra Rottenberg, Hella Rottenberg. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2022] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (228 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tTable Of Contents -- tIsay Rottenberg -- tDöbeln Junction -- tMerchant from Amsterdam -- tKrenter’s Rise and Fall -- tThe Nazis in Power -- tThe Machine Ban -- tA Complaint Filed with the Gestapo -- tGerman Virtue -- tArbeit Und Brot -- tThe Workers Reined In -- tSword and Lightning -- tMünchner Platz -- tUndauntable -- tAnd Then, War -- tBy Robert Rotenberg -- tAcknowledgements -- tList Of Persons -- tFamily Tree -- tGlossary Of Terms and Abbreviations -- tPhoto Credits -- tSources and Bibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1932, Isay Rottenberg, a Jewish paper merchant, bought a cigar factory in Germany: Deutsche Zigarren-Werke. When his competitors, supported by Nazi authorities, tried to shut it down, the headstrong entrepreneur refused to give up the fight. Isay Rottenberg was born into a large Jewish family in Russian Poland in 1889 and grew up in Lodz. He left for Berlin at the age of eighteen to escape military service, moving again in 1917 to Amsterdam on the occasion of his marriage. In 1932 he moved to Germany to take over a bankrupt cigar factory. With newfangled American technology, it was the most modern at the time. The energetic and ambitious Rottenberg was certain he could bring it back to life, and with newly hired staff of 670 workers, the cigar factory was soon back in business. Six months later, Hitler came to power and the Nazi government forbade the use of machines in the cigar industry so that traditional hand-rollers could be re-employed. That was when the real struggle began. More than six hundred qualified machine workers and engineers would lose their jobs if the factory had to close down. Supported by the local authorities he managed to keep the factory going, but in 1935 he was imprisoned following accusations of fraud. The factory was expropriated by the Deutsche Bank. When he was released six months later thanks to the efforts of the Dutch consul, he brought a lawsuit of his own. His fight for rehabilitation and restitution of his property would continue until Kristallnacht in 1938. The Cigar Factory of Isay Rottenberg is written by two of Rottenberg’s granddaughters, who knew little of their grandfather’s past growing up in Amsterdam until a call for claims for stolen or confiscated property started them on a journey of discovery. It includes an afterword by Robert Rotenberg, criminal defense lawyer and author of bestselling legal thrillers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBusinesspeoplezNetherlandsvBiography. 0aCigar industryzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aConfiscationszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewish businesspeoplezNetherlandsvBiography. 0aJewish propertyzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aJews, DutchzGermanyvBiography. 0aJews, PolishzGermanyvBiography. 0aNational socialism. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aGerman Studies. 4aHistory: Jewish Studies. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Jewish.2bisa